<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-066-012 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 235 973</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Sept 2 1991 v13 n35 p89(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hindsight is not always 20/20 for Lotus. (1-2-3 for Windows raisesmore questions about Lotus Development's management)(State of theIndustry) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Parker, Rachel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Lotus Development Corp's management seems determined not to letthe lessons of the past affect present behavior.andP;  With thedebacles of Jazz and Modern Jazz still relatively fresh in theminds of users, if not those of Lotus' management, the firm hasyet again released a product without the necessary fine-tuning.andO;Lotus 1-2-3 for Windows, while fully compatible with 1-2-3 macros,formulae, and formats, is almost painfully slow.andP;  And despite theWindows designation, the interface falls short of true Windowscompliance.andP;  This might be understandable if Lotus was a small,'one-trick pony' operation, forced to hit a market window to haveany chance for survival.andP;  But despite decreasing market share,1-2-3 is still a strong product, and Lotus revenues are furtherbuoyed by a range of other products.andP;  Lotus management must eitherhave chosen to ignore the Jazz lessons, or it is convinced thatthe market will find half a Windows 1-2-3 better than none.andO;Either way, they may be in for a rude awakening.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Lotus Development Corp. (Management).andO;Product:   Lotus 1-2-3 for Windows (Spreadsheet software) (Design andconstruction).andO;Topic:     Software PublishersManagement.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>